<h2 id="20">2. Editing users</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>After creating a user, the new account is displayed in the user overview. Users are listed alphabetically. Select a user to edit the account settings. You may not be able to see all of the settings. The settings that are visible depend on your own user class and on the user class of the user who is being edited. Use the <strong>Group function</strong> to edit multiple users at the same time.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Editing a user account:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Settings » Basic settings » User » Accounts</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Open user</strong>.<br>
→ The user will open in a new tab.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Pay attention to the explanations given in table 2 and carry out the settings as desired.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> the settings.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Password is saved</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The password that you entered when creating your user will not be visible in the editing mode later on but it is saved. You do not have to reenter the password when editing the user account.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="30">2.1. Entering the master data</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Enter information and change the settings of a user account in the <strong>Master data</strong> tab. Only users with administrative rights can edit the <strong>user name</strong>, <strong>IP restriction</strong>, <strong>user class</strong> and <strong>roles</strong>. All other master data can also be changed by a user in his or her own account. In this tab, it is also possible to block a user account.</p>
</div>
